  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Title insurance is one of those products that almost every American property buyer purchases without a second thought and that most Brisbane buyers have never heard of. It is a one-off insurance policy that protects a property owner against financial loss arising from title defects, hidden ownership issues, fraud in the title chain, unregistered easements, and survey errors. You pay a single premium at settlement, and the cover continues for as long as you own the property. If a problem emerges down the track that was not detected by your solicitor's searches, the insurer pays out rather than you funding a legal dispute or settling for a loss of value.</p>

      <p>Title insurance has existed in Australia since the late 1990s but has been slow to become mainstream. The reason is partly historical: Queensland's Torrens title system provides strong statutory guarantees of ownership through the land register, and conveyancing practice in Australia has always relied heavily on those guarantees. Title insurance fills the gaps that Torrens and conveyancing leave open, rather than replacing either of them. For most buyers in Brisbane's inner-east market, it remains an optional rather than a default purchase, but the circumstances where it genuinely earns its premium are worth understanding.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a title defect actually is</h2>
      <p>A title defect is an unresolved ownership or boundary issue that does not show up on a standard title search. Conveyancing due diligence is designed to catch the obvious things: registered mortgages, caveats, easements noted on the title, encumbrances recorded on the dealings register. What conveyancing cannot reliably catch is anything that happened earlier in the title chain and was never properly registered, or anything that should have been recorded but was not.</p>

      <p>Examples of title defects that title insurance is designed to cover include forged signatures in a historical transfer (where a previous owner never actually consented to a sale but the fraud was not detected at the time), unregistered easements where a neighbouring landowner has been using part of your land for many years and may have acquired rights by prescription, boundary encroachments discovered when a new survey is done and a fence turns out to be a metre across the legal boundary, and zoning or planning non-compliance where a structure was built without proper approvals and the issue only surfaces when a later owner tries to sell or renovate.</p>

      <p>The common thread is that these are all problems the current owner did not cause and could not reasonably have detected through standard searches. They are the risks that sit outside what a solicitor is paid to find.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who typically buys title insurance in Queensland</h2>
      <p>In almost all cases, the purchaser is the buyer, not the seller. The policy is taken out as part of the settlement process, usually arranged through the buyer's solicitor or conveyancer. The premium is a one-off payment, typically a few hundred dollars on a standard residential property in Queensland, higher for complex titles or higher-value homes. Cover continues for as long as the buyer owns the property, with no annual renewal and no ongoing premium.</p>

      <p>Sellers can also purchase title insurance, and in specific situations it is worth considering. If you are selling a property with a known historical title quirk (a boundary that does not quite match the fence line, a structure that may have been built without full approvals, a dealings history with unregistered transfers in the family), offering title insurance alongside the listing can strengthen your disclosure position and reduce the risk of a buyer walking away or renegotiating hard on the back of a technical issue. For most straightforward sales, though, sellers do not need to buy title insurance on their own behalf.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers should still understand it</h2>
      <p>Even sellers who have no intention of buying a policy themselves need to understand title insurance, because more buyers are now asking about it as part of their due diligence process. A buyer who has title insurance is generally less likely to walk away from a deal over a minor title concern, because they know the policy will respond if anything turns out to be wrong. That is good news for sellers: it reduces contract-termination risk in the post-inspection phase and makes negotiations over minor title issues less likely to derail the sale.</p>

      <p>On the other hand, a well-advised buyer may ask the seller to provide certain documents or warranties that would not otherwise be part of a standard Queensland contract, because the buyer's insurer wants to see them before issuing a policy. These requests are usually reasonable and easy to accommodate, but it helps to know they are coming so your solicitor can handle them efficiently.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What title insurance typically covers</h2>
      <p>A standard residential title insurance policy in Queensland covers undiscovered easements or encumbrances affecting the property, fraudulent dealings in the title history (including forged signatures in historical transfers), unpaid rates or land tax that were not disclosed at settlement and are later claimed against the property, survey errors where the legal boundary of the property is different from what was shown on pre-sale documents, and zoning or planning non-compliance that pre-dates the current owner's purchase.</p>

      <p>Most policies also cover legal costs associated with defending the owner's title against third-party claims, which can be a significant benefit on its own. The cost of even a modest title dispute can run into tens of thousands of dollars before any question of the underlying property value is resolved.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What it does not cover</h2>
      <p>Title insurance is not a general-purpose property insurance. It does not cover issues that the buyer or seller knew about before the policy was issued. If a defect was disclosed in the contract or discovered during building and pest inspections, it is excluded from cover. It does not cover defects that arise after settlement from the new owner's actions, such as unapproved renovations the new owner commissions. It does not cover general building defects, structural issues, or latent construction problems: those are the domain of building insurance and, to a limited extent, builder's warranty insurance.</p>

      <p>It also does not cover straightforward market risk. If the value of the property declines after settlement for market reasons, that has nothing to do with title and is not something title insurance is designed to address.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How it differs from standard conveyancing protections</h2>
      <p>Conveyancing is a one-off legal service designed to identify issues through searches, title checks, and review of the contract and disclosure documents. It is preventive: the solicitor tries to catch problems before settlement so the buyer can walk away or renegotiate. Title insurance is protective: it responds to problems that were not caught by the searches and that emerge after the buyer has already bought the property.</p>

      <p>The two products work together rather than as alternatives. A good conveyancer reduces the probability that a title insurer will ever need to pay out. The insurer, in turn, covers the residual risk that even the best conveyancing cannot eliminate. For most Queensland buyers, a well-chosen conveyancer is the first line of defence, and title insurance is a sensible top-up for the small number of cases where something was genuinely missed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When it is genuinely useful in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Title insurance earns its premium most clearly on older properties with convoluted title histories. A Queenslander in a suburb that has been through several rounds of subdivision and amalgamation over the decades can easily have dealings in its title chain that are hard to trace. Properties where body corporate or community title arrangements have been restructured, where easements have been created informally between neighbours over many years, or where the house sits close to the legal boundary and the fence line is not quite where it should be, are all cases where a small premium can buy real peace of mind.</p>

      <p>For newer properties in well-documented subdivisions, with clean titles and standard boundaries, the incremental protection of title insurance is smaller. It is still relatively cheap, and many buyers choose to take it out anyway, but the genuine risk being insured is modest.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical advice</h2>
      <p>Title insurance is not required in Queensland, either by law or by lenders. It is an optional product that buyers can choose to purchase on top of their standard conveyancing. For buyers of older Brisbane homes, properties with known historical quirks, or those who simply want the additional layer of protection, the premium is small relative to the value of the property and the transaction cost involved in dealing with a title dispute on your own.</p>

      <p>For sellers, the most useful thing to know is that buyers asking about title insurance are generally doing so as part of a thorough due diligence process, not because they have found a problem with your property. Responding calmly, providing the documents their solicitor or insurer requests, and letting the transaction proceed in the normal way is almost always the right approach. Well-advised buyers are good buyers.</p>

